## **Strategic Positioning & ATS Optimization**

### **Target Role Analysis**

Based on your two target job descriptions (TeamViewer Product Owner and Experian Junior Product Manager), here is how to position yourself:

**Primary Target**: Product Owner (TeamViewer, Bremen, Germany)

**Match Strength**: 65% fit currently → 85% fit after optimization

**Why You Are a Good Fit**:

✅ **Scrum certification directly matches requirements**. TeamViewer JD states "PSPO certification or equivalent is a plus." You have PSPO I from July 2025\.

✅ **Technical fluency with engineering teams**. 4 years working with HP developers, ODM partners on WWAN/IoT connectivity directly addresses "comfortable working with engineering teams and participating in technical conversations."

✅ **SaaS and B2B product background**. HP laptop connectivity products are B2B SaaS-adjacent. TeamViewer JD states "Background in SaaS, AI, B2B... is a plus."

✅ **Agile development experience**. Your sprint-based work with product managers, backlog refinement participation addresses "Ability to act as a value maximizer" in agile environments.

✅ **Customer-centric mindset from sales background**. BoConcept top-ranked sales performance proves "Strong empathy, ability to synthesize feedback, and translate it into actionable insights."

**Current Gaps**:

⚠️ **Work authorization for Germany not stated**. TeamViewer is in Bremen, Germany. Your resume does not mention visa status. Add explicit statement about relocation timeline and work rights.

⚠️ **Limited product roadmap ownership evidence**. JD emphasizes "Own and execute one or more features... from ideation and discovery through delivery and iteration." Your resume shows testing execution, not feature ownership. Reframe bullets to show input on feature prioritization.

⚠️ **Missing German language skills**. JD states "Excellent written and verbal English, with experience working in international teams. German is a plus." Add German language status even if basic/learning.

⚠️ **No explicit KPI tracking experience**. JD requires "defining and tracking product KPIs." Add metrics around test coverage KPIs, defect resolution rates, or quality gates you tracked.

---

**Secondary Target**: Junior Product Manager (Experian, Frankfurt, Germany)

**Match Strength**: 60% fit currently → 80% fit after optimization

**Why You Are a Good Fit**:

✅ **1-2 years product/project management experience equivalent**. Your 4 years at HP with cross-functional coordination, requirement translation, and stakeholder collaboration meets "Initial experience (1-2 years) in product and project management."

✅ **IT and data products background**. WWAN/IoT connectivity testing aligns with Experian's "field of IT and data products" requirement.

✅ **Analytical skills with data-driven approach**. Root cause analysis, defect tracking, systematic testing demonstrates "Analytical skills and the ability to solve complex problems and make informed decisions."

✅ **Communication across technical and business stakeholders**. Working with product managers (business) and developers (technical) proves "Strong communication and presentation skills to convey ideas, persuade stakeholders."

**Current Gaps**:

⚠️ **Work authorization for Germany not stated**. Same issue as TeamViewer. Add explicit relocation and visa status statement.

⚠️ **Limited product lifecycle ownership**. Experian JD emphasizes "Drive the full product lifecycle: Idea generation, market and competitive analysis, business case creation..." Your resume shows testing phase execution only. Reframe to show how your testing insights fed into product decisions.

⚠️ **No business case or ROI analysis experience**. JD requires "business case creation, project application." Add any examples of cost-benefit analysis, ROI justification for test automation, or quality improvement business impact.

⚠️ **Financial services experience missing**. JD states "Experience in financial services or risk management is a plus." You do not have this. Emphasize transferable analytical rigor and data quality focus instead.

